Here's an example of a binary search algorithm implemented in Java:
```java
public class BinarySearch {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] sortedArray = {10, 12, 15, 20, 25, 30, 35};
        int target = 25;

        int resultIndex = binarySearch(sortedArray, target);

        if (resultIndex != -1) {
            System.out.println("Target found at index: " + resultIndex);
        } else {
            System.out.println("Target not found in the array.");
        }
    }

    public static int binarySearch(int[] array, int target) {
        int low = 0;
        int high = array.length - 1;

        while (low <= high) {
            int mid = (low + high) / 2;

            if (array[mid] == target) {
                return mid;
            } else if (array[mid] < target) {
                low = mid + 1;
            } else {
                high = mid - 1;
            }
        }

        return -1; // Target not found
    }
}
```
This implementation uses a binary search algorithm to find a specific element (target) in a sorted array (sortedArray). The algorithm first checks whether the target is present in the array by stepping through the array starting from the middle element. If the target is found, the index of the element is returned. If the target is not found, the function returns -1.

